THE PRODUCT WAS SPILLED IN A CONTAINED AREA AT THE PLANT LOCATION. CUSTOMER EMPLOYEES DUG UP DIRT FROM THE AREA OF THE SPILL AND SPREAD IT IN A THIN LAYER OVER A LARGE VACANT PORTION OF THEIR PROPERTY. FRESH DIRT WAS BROUGHT IN TO REPLACE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL.

CAUSE OF SPILL:  AN EXPERIENCED LOADER AND NEW MAN WERE WORKING AFTER HOURS TRANSLOADING FERRIC CHLORIDE FROM A RAIL CAR TO A TANK TRAILER. THE LOADER MADE A DECISION TO USE AN UNAUTHORIZED COMPRESSOR. THIS COMPRESSOR APPARENTLY WAS OF GREATER POWER THAN THE APPROVED COMPRESSOR AND WAS NOT EQUIPPED WITH A PRESSURE GUAGE. THIS APPARENTLY RESULTED IN EXCESS PRESSURIZATION OF THE RAIL CAR. ON DETERMINATION THAT SUFFICIENT PRODUCT HAD BEEN TRANSLOADED TO THE TRAILER, THE LOADER, WHO WAS ON THE GROUND, INSTRUCTED THE ASSISTANT ON TOP OF THE RAIL CAR TO CLOSE THE VALVE. ON APPLYING PRESSURE TO CLOSE THE VALVE, THE VALVE BROKE. PRODUCT UNDER PRESSURE IN THE RAIL CAR WAS FORCED OUT OF THE UNRESTRICTED VALVE OPENING. AMOUNT LOST:   IT IS ESTIMATED THAT APPROXIMATELY 6,000 GALLONS OF PRODUCT WAS LOST. THIS IS DETERMINED BY GUAGING THE RAIL CAR. REMEDIAL ACTION TAKEN:  FOUR SEASONS ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES WAS CALLED IMMEDIATELY AT TIME OF SPILL AND WERE ON THE SCENE IN APROXIMATELY FOUR HOURS. THE FERRIC CHLORIDE WAS CONTAINED, COLLECTED AND REMOVED.  A COPY OF THE CLEAN UP COMPANY'S ACTIVITY REPORT IS ATTACHED. PREVENTIVE MEASURES PLANNED:  1. EMPLOYMENT OF THE LOADER HAS BEEN TERMINATED FOR FAILURE TO FOLLOW ESTABLISHED PROCEDURE. 2. THE UNAUTHORIZED COMPRESSOR HAS BEEN REMOVED FROM THE PREMISES.  ALL LOADER HAVE BEEN INSTRUCTED TO FOLLOW ESTABLISHED PROCEDURE AND TO USE ONLY AUTHORIZED EQUIPMENT. 3. A STAINLESS STEEL OR OTHER METAL VALVE WITH APPROPRIATE LINING IS BEING SECURED FOR USE ON THE RAIL CAR.  WHILE THE PVC VALVE IS CONSIDERED SATISFACTORY SINCE THE PRODUCT REQUIRES LINED VESSEL AND FITTINGS, IT IS FELT THE METAL VALVE WILL PROVIDE ADDITIONAL STRENGTH AND PROTECTION.  IT IS OUR OPINION THAT THE NATURE OF THIS PRODUCT AND THE PROMPT CONTAINMENT ACTION BY THE LOCAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE PERSONNEL AS WELL AS THE FURTHER CONTAINMENT AND REMEDIAL ACTION OF FOUR SEASONS PREVENTED ANY IMMEDIATE OF LONG TERM THREAT TO THE ENVIRONMENT, FISH OR WILD LIFE.

WITHIN A SHORT PERIOD OF TIME, O NE OF THREE LOADERS, JOAN HESSELTON, BECAME ILL. THE SUPERVISOR, BOB FORCIE R, FOUND THE PACKAGE TO CONTAIN APPROXIMATELY ONE GALLON OF TETRAHYDROFURAN IN A BOX WITHIN A BOX WITH A CRACKED CAP. EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK WAS CHECKED, POISON CENTER CALLED AND CHECKUP AT ST VINCENTS HOSPITAL IN WORCE STER, MA., WAS ARRANGED FOR THE EMPLOYEE. BOTTLE CAP WAS TOO TIGHT TO THE T OP OF THE CARTON, AND NO TOP PADDING, NO CARTON MARKINGS.

KREVIT DRIVER ARRIVED AT 8:10 AM. TOLD RECEIVER HE HAD 1800 GALLONS OF SULF URIC ACID ON TRUCK. AT ABOUT 0900 AM, THE RECEIVER CAME OUT TO THE DRIVER A ND TOLD HIM TO SHUT DOWN BECAUSE THE TANK WAS RUNNING OVER. THE DRIVER SHUT DOWN AND CALLED THE OFFICE. I ARRIVED AT EAST COAST AT ABOUT 9:20 A.M. I S POKE WITH JOHN CORANGELO. HE TOLD ME THAT THEY CONTAINED THE SPILL AND BEIN G PUMPED INTO THEIR RECOVERY TANK. THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE CT D.E.P. EAST COAST RECEIVED 1159 GALLONS OF THE 1800 ORDERED. I BELIEVE THAT A HIGH LEVEL ALARM SHOULD BE INSTALLED IN THIS STORAGE TANK. I HAVE RECOMMEDED EA ST COAST DO SO ASAP. IN THE INTERIM, EAST COAST WILL USE A TEO-WAY RADIO SY STEM BETWEEN UNLOADING TRUCKS AND RECEIVERS AT THE TANK SITE.

column168: DURING SWITCHING OPERATIONS CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING IN DIP PIPE AREA OF MANWAY COVER.  CAR WAS PLACED TO AN ISOLATED TRACK FOR INSPECTION AND REPAIRS.  CHEMTREC, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.  DOW CHEMICAL ADVISED THAT MR. PERRY WOULD BE OUT TO INSPECT AND MAKE NECESSARY REPAIRS.  MR. PERRY ARRIVED AT 10 A.M. AND REPAIRED THE DIP PIPE AND CAR WAS OK TO CONTINUE TO DESTINATION.
